<ArticleLayout
  title="Under-Sink Bathroom Storage: What to Check Before Buying Organisers"
  description="Before buying under-sink bathroom organisers, check pipe position, cabinet depth, shelf height, leaks, moisture, cleaning products, child access and what actually needs to be stored there."
  category="Bathroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bathroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A bathroom vanity cabinet with practical under-sink storage and warm natural light"
>
  <p>
    Under-sink bathroom storage is useful, but it is rarely a simple rectangular space. Pipes,
    traps, hoses, shelf cut-outs, cabinet doors, damp corners and awkward depths can make
    standard organisers a poor fit.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is also a space where problems can be hidden. Leaks, spills, cleaning products, damp
    cloths, loose razors and forgotten bottles can sit behind baskets for months if the
    storage is not planned carefully.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying under-sink shelves, baskets, pull-out organisers, stackable drawers or
    tubs, check the actual cabinet space and what needs to be stored there.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to check before buying under-sink bathroom organisers.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what belongs under the sink</h2>
  <p>
    The under-sink cabinet should not become the default place for every bathroom item.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying organisers, decide what genuinely belongs there.
  </p>
  <p>Common under-sink items include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>spare soap</li>
    <li>spare toothpaste</li>
    <li>toilet paper</li>
    <li>spare shampoo or conditioner</li>
    <li>skincare backups</li>
    <li>shaving supplies</li>
    <li>cleaning cloths</li>
    <li>bathroom cleaning products</li>
    <li>toilet cleaner</li>
    <li>spare hand towels</li>
    <li>travel toiletries</li>
    <li>hair products</li>
    <li>first-aid items</li>
    <li>razors or blades</li>
    <li>small grooming tools</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Not all of these are good fits for every household. Some items may need controlled
    storage. Some may not suit moisture. Some may be better stored in a linen cupboard,
    laundry, hallway cupboard or higher cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not buy under-sink organisers until you know what the space actually needs to hold.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove old products first</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink cabinets often collect products that are no longer used.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage, remove:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty bottles</li>
    <li>expired toiletries</li>
    <li>old cosmetics</li>
    <li>products that smell unusual</li>
    <li>products that have changed texture</li>
    <li>duplicate items</li>
    <li>leaking bottles</li>
    <li>damp cloths</li>
    <li>mystery containers</li>
    <li>broken razors or packaging</li>
    <li>old travel toiletries</li>
    <li>cleaning products you no longer use</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This step can reduce the amount of storage needed. It also helps you see whether the
    cabinet has dampness, stains, leaks or damage that should be checked before adding
    organisers.
  </p>
  <p>
    If medicines, cosmetics, skincare or cleaning products are expired or questionable,
    follow product labels or appropriate disposal guidance.
  </p>

  <h2>Check for leaks, dampness and damage before organising</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage can hide small problems.
  </p>
  <p>Before placing baskets or shelves inside the cabinet, inspect the space.</p>
  <p>Look for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>water marks</li>
    <li>swollen cabinet panels</li>
    <li>peeling surfaces</li>
    <li>mould-prone corners</li>
    <li>musty smells</li>
    <li>damp cloths</li>
    <li>loose pipe fittings</li>
    <li>stains under bottles</li>
    <li>signs of past leaks</li>
    <li>rusted items</li>
    <li>pest activity</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not treat storage as the fix for a damp or leaking cabinet. If there are signs of
    leaks, water damage, mould or plumbing issues, seek appropriate advice before loading the
    space with organisers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage should make the cabinet easier to inspect, not harder.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure around the pipes</h2>
  <p>
    The main under-sink mistake is measuring the cabinet as if the pipes are not there.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying organisers, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>total cabinet width</li>
    <li>total cabinet depth</li>
    <li>total cabinet height</li>
    <li>pipe position from the back wall</li>
    <li>pipe position from each side</li>
    <li>trap height and width</li>
    <li>flexible hose position</li>
    <li>shelf cut-outs</li>
    <li>any fixed dividers</li>
    <li>cabinet door opening</li>
    <li>hinge clearance</li>
    <li>usable flat floor space</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Draw a simple sketch if needed. Mark where the pipe, trap and hoses sit.
  </p>
  <p>
    An organiser can fit the cabinet width but still clash with the pipe. A pull-out drawer
    can fit the floor but not slide around the trap. A stacking shelf can fit one side but
    block access to plumbing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the usable space, not the empty-looking space.
  </p>

  <h2>Check cabinet depth and door clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink organisers often fail because they are too deep or cannot be accessed properly.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying baskets, tubs or pull-out organisers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cabinet depth at floor level</li>
    <li>cabinet depth around pipes</li>
    <li>whether doors open fully</li>
    <li>whether hinges reduce usable width</li>
    <li>whether a basket can slide out</li>
    <li>whether a drawer handle will hit the door frame</li>
    <li>whether stored bottles will be reachable at the back</li>
    <li>whether the organiser can be removed for cleaning</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet has a centre divider</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Deep storage can be useful, but only if items can still be seen and reached.
  </p>
  <p>
    If products disappear at the back of the cabinet, the organiser may hide clutter rather
    than solve it.
  </p>

  <h2>Check bottle height before buying shelves</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom bottles are often taller than expected.
  </p>
  <p>Before choosing shelves, risers or stackable drawers, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>toilet cleaner bottles</li>
    <li>spray bottles</li>
    <li>shampoo bottles</li>
    <li>skincare bottles</li>
    <li>spare body wash</li>
    <li>shaving cream</li>
    <li>sunscreen</li>
    <li>contact solution</li>
    <li>hair products</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>tall pump bottles</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shelf may fit inside the cabinet but leave no room for bottles to stand upright. Laying
    bottles down can increase the chance of leaks or make products harder to identify.
  </p>
  <p>
    If bottles need to stand upright, measure height with lids, pumps and caps included.
  </p>

  <h2>Be cautious with pull-out organisers</h2>
  <p>
    Pull-out organisers can improve access, but they do not suit every under-sink cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying one, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>pipe position</li>
    <li>cabinet width</li>
    <li>cabinet depth</li>
    <li>door hinge clearance</li>
    <li>whether the organiser needs fixing</li>
    <li>whether the drawer clears the trap</li>
    <li>whether bottles will stay upright when pulled</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet floor can support the loaded organiser</li>
    <li>whether installation is allowed in a rental</li>
    <li>whether the organiser can be removed for cleaning</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A pull-out organiser that looks useful may not work if the plumbing sits in the way or if
    the cabinet doors restrict movement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not drill, screw or permanently attach anything inside a rental vanity without
    checking approval where needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide between baskets, tubs, shelves and drawers</h2>
  <p>
    Different under-sink organisers suit different items.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Organiser type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Open baskets</td>
        <td>grouped toiletries, spare supplies</td>
        <td>moisture, label visibility, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Plastic tubs</td>
        <td>backup products, grouped categories</td>
        <td>size, lid use, spills, weight</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Stackable drawers</td>
        <td>small items, grooming products</td>
        <td>height, pipe clearance, drawer access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Small shelves</td>
        <td>vertical space on one side of pipes</td>
        <td>bottle height, stability, cabinet depth</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Pull-out organisers</td>
        <td>deep cabinets and frequent-use items</td>
        <td>pipe clearance, fixing, door swing</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Divided containers</td>
        <td>razors, accessories, small products</td>
        <td>controlled access, cleanability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Caddies</td>
        <td>cleaning products used around the bathroom</td>
        <td>bottle height, handle clearance</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    A useful under-sink setup often uses one or two simple organisers rather than filling
    every centimetre.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep categories visible</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage becomes frustrating when every basket is a mixed category.
  </p>
  <p>Use clear, simple groups such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>spare toothpaste and toothbrush heads</li>
    <li>hair products</li>
    <li>shaving supplies</li>
    <li>spare soap and body wash</li>
    <li>bathroom cleaning products</li>
    <li>toilet paper</li>
    <li>guest toiletries</li>
    <li>travel toiletries</li>
    <li>first-aid items, if suitable</li>
    <li>spare hand towels</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid vague categories such as "bathroom stuff" or "miscellaneous". These usually become
    long-term clutter zones.
  </p>
  <p>
    Labels can help, especially in shared bathrooms. Place labels where they can be seen when
    the cabinet is opened.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate cleaning products from toiletries</h2>
  <p>
    Cleaning products should not be mixed with grooming products, towels or spare toiletries.
  </p>
  <p>
    If cleaning products are stored under the bathroom sink, keep them clearly separated.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>product label storage instructions</li>
    <li>whether bottles stand upright</li>
    <li>whether lids are secure</li>
    <li>whether products could leak</li>
    <li>whether children or pets can access them</li>
    <li>whether incompatible products need separation</li>
    <li>whether cloths or brushes need drying</li>
    <li>whether cleaning products should be stored somewhere else</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not place cleaning products where leaks could drip onto toothbrush heads, towels,
    cosmetics or skincare.
  </p>
  <p>
    For cleaning products, follow product labels and seek appropriate advice where needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully about medicines and first aid</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink cabinets are not always suitable for medicines or first aid.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bathrooms can be humid, warm and accessible to children or pets. Under-sink spaces can
    also be damp or close to cleaning products.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before storing medicines under the sink, check product labels or pharmacist guidance.
    Some items may need to be stored away from moisture, heat or children.
  </p>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>prescription medicines</li>
    <li>children's medicines</li>
    <li>tablets and capsules</li>
    <li>creams and ointments</li>
    <li>bandages</li>
    <li>antiseptics</li>
    <li>thermometers</li>
    <li>first-aid tools</li>
    <li>expired items</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If first-aid items remain in the bathroom, keep them clearly separated from cleaning
    products and controlled where needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Control razors, blades and sharp items</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink cabinets can be easy for children or pets to access, depending on the home.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before storing sharp items under the sink, decide how they will be controlled.
  </p>
  <p>Items needing caution include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>spare blades</li>
    <li>scissors</li>
    <li>tweezers</li>
    <li>nail tools</li>
    <li>grooming blades</li>
    <li>small sharp accessories</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid loose blades in open baskets. Avoid placing sharp items in low, easy-access
    containers where children can reach them.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small labelled container inside a controlled area may be more practical than loose
    storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with damp towels and cloths</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage is not always suitable for damp fabric.
  </p>
  <p>Before storing towels, face washers, cleaning cloths or bath cloths, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether they are fully dry</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet has airflow</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet smells damp</li>
    <li>whether cloths are used with cleaning products</li>
    <li>whether the fabric touches pipes or damp surfaces</li>
    <li>whether the organiser traps moisture</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Damp towels or cloths in closed baskets can create odour and moisture problems. If towels
    are stored under the sink, they should be dry and easy to remove for washing.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep access to plumbing visible</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink organisers should not hide everything behind a wall of storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Leave enough access to see and reach the plumbing area if needed.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>packing bottles tightly around pipes</li>
    <li>placing heavy organisers against hoses</li>
    <li>hiding leaks behind sealed containers</li>
    <li>blocking access to valves or fittings</li>
    <li>storing items so tightly that nothing can be removed quickly</li>
    <li>using organisers that must be dismantled to inspect the space</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    You do not need to leave the cabinet empty, but storage should not make basic inspection
    impossible.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider children and pets</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink cabinets are often low and easy to reach.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying open baskets or low drawers, check whether children or pets could access:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>medicines</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>cosmetics</li>
    <li>fragrances</li>
    <li>small items that could be swallowed</li>
    <li>glass containers</li>
    <li>grooming tools</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Open storage can be convenient, but it may not suit every household.
  </p>
  <p>
    Controlled storage matters more than making the cabinet look neat.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about shared bathrooms</h2>
  <p>
    Shared bathrooms need clearer under-sink categories.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying organisers, decide whether the cabinet needs:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>one basket per person</li>
    <li>one basket per routine</li>
    <li>separate cleaning product storage</li>
    <li>separate backup supplies</li>
    <li>a guest toiletries section</li>
    <li>a travel toiletries section</li>
    <li>a first-aid section, if suitable</li>
    <li>a spare toilet paper zone</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If several people use the same cabinet, labels and simple categories are usually more
    useful than many small unlabelled containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is to make items easy to find and return without one person having to reset the
    whole cabinet.
  </p>

  <h2>Watch for moisture and material choice</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink cabinets can be exposed to moisture, spills and damp air.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before choosing organisers, check whether the material suits the space.
  </p>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cardboard boxes</li>
    <li>untreated timber</li>
    <li>fabric baskets</li>
    <li>paper labels</li>
    <li>metal items that may rust</li>
    <li>containers that trap water</li>
    <li>organisers that cannot be cleaned easily</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Plastic tubs or wipeable baskets may suit some under-sink areas better than fabric or
    cardboard, but the right choice depends on the cabinet condition and what is being stored.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the cabinet has persistent dampness, deal with the cause rather than relying on
    containers.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid overfilling the cabinet</h2>
  <p>
    An organised under-sink cabinet should still have breathing room.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid filling every gap with bottles, baskets and drawers. Leave space to:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>see the pipes</li>
    <li>remove items easily</li>
    <li>clean spills</li>
    <li>check for leaks</li>
    <li>keep labels visible</li>
    <li>return products without rearranging everything</li>
    <li>remove organisers for cleaning</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the cabinet is full immediately after organising, it may be holding too many
    categories.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some spare supplies may belong outside the bathroom.
  </p>

  <h2>Common under-sink bathroom storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Before buying, avoid these mistakes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying organisers without measuring around pipes</li>
    <li>choosing pull-out drawers that hit the trap or hinges</li>
    <li>storing cleaning products with toiletries</li>
    <li>hiding leaks behind baskets</li>
    <li>using fabric or cardboard in damp cabinets</li>
    <li>storing medicines in a humid space without checking guidance</li>
    <li>leaving razors or blades loose</li>
    <li>overfilling the cabinet with spare supplies</li>
    <li>blocking access to plumbing</li>
    <li>choosing shelves that do not fit bottle height</li>
    <li>putting damp cloths into closed containers</li>
    <li>using vague labels</li>
    <li>assuming all under-sink spaces are standard</li>
    <li>drilling or fixing products in a rental without checking approval</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage should improve access and visibility, not hide problems.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple under-sink checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying under-sink bathroom organisers, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cabinet width, depth and height</li>
    <li>pipe and trap position</li>
    <li>door hinge clearance</li>
    <li>whether doors open fully</li>
    <li>shelf height or fixed shelf position</li>
    <li>bottle heights</li>
    <li>cleaning products to separate</li>
    <li>toiletries that need backup storage</li>
    <li>medicines or first-aid items needing label or pharmacist guidance</li>
    <li>razors and blades needing controlled storage</li>
    <li>child and pet access concerns</li>
    <li>signs of leaks, dampness or mould</li>
    <li>whether organisers can be removed and cleaned</li>
    <li>whether labels will be visible</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet needs space for plumbing access</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
    <li>what can be stored somewhere else</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before buying. Under-sink organisers need to fit around real plumbing,
    not just the cabinet dimensions.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink bathroom storage should start with inspection and measurement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remove expired, empty and unused products first. Check for leaks, dampness and damage.
    Measure around pipes, traps, hoses, hinges and shelf gaps before buying organisers. Keep
    cleaning products separate from toiletries, control razors and medicines, and avoid
    blocking access to plumbing.
  </p>
  <p>
    For most households, a useful under-sink setup is simple: a few labelled, wipeable
    organisers that fit the cabinet properly and can be removed for cleaning.
  </p>
  <p>
    If an organiser hides leaks, blocks pipes, traps moisture or mixes hazardous items with
    daily toiletries, it is not solving the real storage problem.
  </p>

